1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:28,501
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

2
00:00:30,861 --> 00:00:38,892
So now we've come to a particular discourse which is really asking the question, you know, what makes a good life?

3
00:00:39,412 --> 00:00:45,320
And again you have to translate a lot of what the Buddha said into the modern idiom.

4
00:00:46,421 --> 00:00:50,987
So I shall read it and then we'll see what we can say about it.

5
00:00:52,990 --> 00:01:00,378
Now on one occasion the Blessed One was dwelling among the Kaliyans where there was a market town of the Kaliyans called Kakarapata.

6
00:01:01,456 --> 00:01:12,868
Then the Kalyan family man Dīgha Janu approached the Blessed One, paid homage to him, sat down to one side, and so seated he said to the Blessed One, Venerable Sir, we are lay people.

7
00:01:13,248 --> 00:01:24,602
We enjoy sensual pleasure, dwelling at home in a bed crowded with children, enjoying fine sandalwood, wearing garlands, scents and unguents, accepting gold and silver.

8
00:01:25,503 --> 00:01:30,349
Let the Blessed One teach the Dharma to us in a way that will lead to our welfare and happiness.

9
00:01:30,802 --> 00:01:33,766
both in the present life and in the future life as well.

10
00:01:34,929 --> 00:01:41,718
So, you know, that sentence, crowded with children, a bed crowded with children.

11
00:01:42,641 --> 00:01:46,968
Like Eskimos, the Tibetans also, the whole family sleeps in the same bed.

12
00:01:46,987 --> 00:01:51,754
They don't have mummy and daddy over there and the rest of them in the back room, you know.

13
00:01:54,659 --> 00:01:55,340
So...

14
00:01:55,927 --> 00:02:03,456
There they are, you see, just like these days, sensual pleasures, enjoying fine sandalwood and all that, and accepting gold and silver.

15
00:02:04,418 --> 00:02:08,103
So remember, in those days, that was fairly new.

16
00:02:08,143 --> 00:02:09,003
You had to be rich.

17
00:02:09,063 --> 00:02:11,347
There was still mainly society with barter.

18
00:02:12,146 --> 00:02:17,454
So this was the beginning of the merchant class.

19
00:02:17,473 --> 00:02:24,282
There are, by Biagapadja, four things that lead to the welfare and happiness of a family man in this very life.

20
00:02:25,020 --> 00:02:33,072
So you have to translate this family man to a couple or whatever.

21
00:02:34,394 --> 00:02:34,914
What for?

22
00:02:35,275 --> 00:02:42,044
Accomplishment of persistent effort, the accomplishment of protection, good friendship and balanced living.

23
00:02:43,026 --> 00:02:45,429
And what is the accomplishment of persistent effort?

24
00:02:45,889 --> 00:02:54,842
Here, Biyagabhaja, whatever may be the means by which a family man earns his living, whether by farming, trade, cattle raising,

25
00:02:55,328 --> 00:03:01,034
archery, or civil service, or by any other craft, he is skillful and diligent.

26
00:03:01,756 --> 00:03:06,762
He investigates the appropriate means and is able to act and arrange everything properly.

27
00:03:07,323 --> 00:03:10,507
This is called accomplishment of persistent effort.

28
00:03:10,526 --> 00:03:11,707
In other words, you do a good job.

29
00:03:13,770 --> 00:03:15,612
I mean, that's pretty straightforward.

30
00:03:18,116 --> 00:03:20,058
And what is the accomplishment of protection?

31
00:03:20,659 --> 00:03:25,064
Here, Biagapaja, a family man sets up a protection and guard

32
00:03:25,484 --> 00:03:43,379
over the wealth acquired by energetic striving, amassed by the strength of his arms, earned by the sweat of his brow, righteous wealth righteously gained, thinking, how can I prevent kings and bandits from taking this away?

33
00:03:44,180 --> 00:03:50,626
Fire from burning it, floods from sweeping it, and unloved heirs from taking it.

34
00:03:52,167 --> 00:03:55,389
This is called accomplishment of protection.

35
00:03:57,461 --> 00:03:59,084
Well, there's not so much that.

36
00:03:59,104 --> 00:04:00,105
It's just, yes, exactly.

37
00:04:00,145 --> 00:04:07,034
I was going to say kings and governments taking away our money and bandits.

38
00:04:07,395 --> 00:04:10,058
And, of course, now we have insurance, so we're not too worried about these things.

39
00:04:10,379 --> 00:04:16,348
But I love that unloved airs from taking it away.

40
00:04:16,367 --> 00:04:18,170
And what is good friendship?

41
00:04:18,189 --> 00:04:26,000
Here, Biaga Padgap, is whatever village, oh, sorry, in whatever village or town a family man dwells,

42
00:04:26,351 --> 00:04:36,942
He associates with householders or their sons, whether young or old, who are of a mature virtue, accomplished in faith, moral discipline, generosity and wisdom.

43
00:04:37,682 --> 00:04:41,286
He converses with them and engages in discussions with them.

44
00:04:41,305 --> 00:04:47,791
He emulates them in regard to their accomplishment in faith, moral discipline, generosity and wisdom.

45
00:04:48,172 --> 00:04:49,514
This is called good friendship.

46
00:04:50,093 --> 00:04:53,237
So that's the definition of good friendship, you see.

47
00:04:54,617 --> 00:05:00,103
Faith, he goes on actually to describe faith as having faith in the Buddha Dhammasanga.

48
00:05:00,124 --> 00:05:02,045
But it's also trust, isn't it?

49
00:05:02,807 --> 00:05:03,788
Trust in each other.

50
00:05:04,567 --> 00:05:05,468
Model discipline.

51
00:05:06,410 --> 00:05:08,012
He also explains that afterwards.

52
00:05:09,213 --> 00:05:10,694
Generosity and wisdom.

53
00:05:11,355 --> 00:05:14,278
As I say, he comes to that, so we'll read that for the time being.

54
00:05:16,040 --> 00:05:17,461
And what is a balanced life?

55
00:05:17,762 --> 00:05:23,307
Here, Bhiyagapajara, a family man knows his income and expenditures and leaves the balanced life

56
00:05:23,557 --> 00:05:52,165
neither extravagant nor miserly so that his income exceeds his expenditures rather than the reverse just as a goldsmith or his apprentice holding up a scale knows by so much it has dipped down by so much it has tilted up so a family man leads a balanced life the wealth thus amassed has right so that's interesting because as you know these days everybody seems everybody's in debt the average debt is eight thousand pounds

57
00:05:52,600 --> 00:05:54,060
as what is on the news.

58
00:05:54,841 --> 00:05:59,346
Our society has not been living the balanced life.

59
00:06:00,107 --> 00:06:03,629
And so we've ended up in this dreadful place.

60
00:06:05,432 --> 00:06:08,834
The wealth thus amassed has four sources of dissipation.

61
00:06:09,576 --> 00:06:14,240
Womanizing, drunkenness, gambling and evil friendship.

62
00:06:14,259 --> 00:06:20,346
Just as in the case of a tank with four inlets and outlets, if one should close the inlets and open the outlets,

63
00:06:20,713 --> 00:06:26,759
and there would be not enough adequate rainfall, a decrease rather than increase of the water could be expected in the tank.

64
00:06:27,380 --> 00:06:31,324
So these four things bring about dissipation of amassed wealth.

65
00:06:31,343 --> 00:06:35,709
Similarly, there are four sources for the increase of amassed wealth.

66
00:06:35,728 --> 00:06:40,293
Abstinence from womanizing, from drunkenness, from gambling, and from evil friendship.

67
00:06:41,014 --> 00:06:47,160
And just as in the case of a tank with four inlets and outlets, if one should open the inlets and close the outlets,

68
00:06:47,528 --> 00:06:49,009
And there would be adequate rainfall.

69
00:06:49,250 --> 00:06:54,177
An increase, rather than a decrease, of the water could be expected in the tank.

70
00:06:54,218 --> 00:06:56,841
These four things bring about the increase of amassed wealth.

71
00:06:57,442 --> 00:06:59,927
So this tells you what people got up to.

72
00:07:00,548 --> 00:07:01,970
All sorts of clubbing.

73
00:07:04,894 --> 00:07:05,776
Drunkenness.

74
00:07:05,795 --> 00:07:10,182
This is not new, is it?

75
00:07:13,166 --> 00:07:13,367
Yes.

76
00:07:14,291 --> 00:07:20,838
And there are four things, Bhāgapājā, lead a family man's welfare and happiness in the present life.

77
00:07:21,879 --> 00:07:28,286
These four things, Bhāgapājā, lead to a family man's welfare and happiness in his present life.

78
00:07:28,827 --> 00:07:33,452
Four other things lead to a family man's welfare and happiness in the future life.

79
00:07:33,713 --> 00:07:34,254
What for?

80
00:07:35,055 --> 00:07:39,600
Accomplishment in faith, moral discipline, generosity and wisdom.

81
00:07:40,420 --> 00:07:42,603
And how is a family man accomplished in faith?

82
00:07:43,163 --> 00:07:44,264
Here Bhāgapājā

83
00:07:44,565 --> 00:07:45,807
A family man has faith.

84
00:07:45,846 --> 00:07:48,550
He places faith in the enlightenment of the Tathagata.

85
00:07:49,190 --> 00:08:03,985
So the Blessed One is an Arahat, perfectly enlightened, accomplished in true knowledge and conduct, fortunate, knower of the world, unsurpassed leader of persons to be tamed, teacher of devas and humans, the Enlightened One, the Blessed One.

86
00:08:04,326 --> 00:08:08,309
In this way, a family man is accomplished in faith.

87
00:08:09,591 --> 00:08:13,915
So this basically is pointing to the fact that

88
00:08:14,283 --> 00:08:17,887
We need a spiritual hero, really, to emulate.

89
00:08:19,170 --> 00:08:21,733
Somebody who guides us, a teacher.

90
00:08:22,475 --> 00:08:24,218
I mean, they're lucky to have the Buddha.

91
00:08:26,961 --> 00:08:28,925
So it puts them in a slightly better position.

92
00:08:29,947 --> 00:08:32,650
And how is a family man accomplished in moral discipline?

93
00:08:34,293 --> 00:08:40,763
Here, Bhiyagapajara, a family man abstains from the destruction of life, from stealing, from sexual misconduct, from false speech.

94
00:08:41,350 --> 00:08:44,936
And from wines, liquors, and intoxicants, the basis of negligence.

95
00:08:44,956 --> 00:08:47,580
And this way a family man is accomplished in moral discipline.

96
00:08:48,241 --> 00:08:54,812
You'll notice that wines, liquors, and intoxicants, he didn't consider them to be evil in themselves.

97
00:08:54,893 --> 00:08:58,438
It was more that it led to this basis for negligence.

98
00:08:58,458 --> 00:09:00,722
You do things under the influence that you wouldn't normally do.

99
00:09:03,586 --> 00:09:06,312
And how is a family man accomplished in generosity?

100
00:09:06,552 --> 00:09:07,594
Here, Bhiyagapadya,

101
00:09:08,047 --> 00:09:21,761
A family man dwells at home with a mind devoid of the stain of stinginess, freely generous, open-handed, delighted in relinquishment, one devoted to charity, delighting in giving and sharing.

102
00:09:22,001 --> 00:09:24,985
And in this way, a family man is accomplished in generosity.

103
00:09:26,447 --> 00:09:28,208
And how is a man accomplished in wisdom?

104
00:09:28,629 --> 00:09:35,876
Here, Bhiyagapadya, a family man possesses the wisdom that sees into the arising and passing away of phenomena.

105
00:09:36,498 --> 00:09:41,501
that is noble and penetrative and leads to the complete destruction of suffering.

106
00:09:41,522 --> 00:09:43,884
In this way, a family man is accomplished in wisdom.

107
00:09:44,684 --> 00:09:53,131
These four things, Bhīyāgapājā, lead to a family man's welfare and happiness in a future life.

108
00:09:53,152 --> 00:10:05,543
So, having made clear what he feels makes us happy in this life, this persistent effort, doing a good job, protecting what one has,

109
00:10:06,248 --> 00:10:16,519
a balanced life, a good friendship and a balanced life.

110
00:10:16,679 --> 00:10:24,970
Persistent effort, doing a good job, protecting what one has, good friendship and a balanced life.

111
00:10:27,133 --> 00:10:29,014
And that is it.

112
00:10:29,034 --> 00:10:35,142
Now when he talks about future life, future birth,

113
00:10:36,251 --> 00:10:44,722
which we can either take to mean after death, or just this life, the future of this life.

114
00:10:46,205 --> 00:10:52,232
The first thing he points to is that we need to have some sort of guide, a spiritual guide.

115
00:10:55,378 --> 00:10:57,500
And then he says to accomplish in moral discipline.

116
00:10:57,821 --> 00:11:05,331
Remember that in the Buddha's teaching, our unethical behavior is the measure of our delusion.

117
00:11:06,239 --> 00:11:34,542
that's why morality ethics and wisdom go hand in hand you can't have the one without the other because the impurity in our hearts is caused by this deep wrong understanding which always begins with seeking happiness in the wrong place because we seek happiness in the wrong place we

118
00:11:34,807 --> 00:11:37,250
we become attached to it, we hold on to things.

119
00:11:38,410 --> 00:11:42,094
And that develops into greed, and at worst into stealing, things like that.

120
00:11:42,975 --> 00:11:50,662
And when we do that, anybody who threatens what we have becomes our enemy.

121
00:11:51,503 --> 00:11:52,903
Find ourselves in conflict.

122
00:11:52,923 --> 00:11:54,085
So aversion arises.

123
00:11:55,586 --> 00:11:57,106
And if that person's too big, fear.

124
00:11:57,628 --> 00:11:58,168
You run for it.

125
00:11:58,769 --> 00:12:03,533
So there's your three basic dispositions

126
00:12:04,288 --> 00:12:08,573
from the position of delusion, acquisitiveness, aversion, and fear.

127
00:12:10,216 --> 00:12:12,238
And from there, all the miseries arise.

128
00:12:14,280 --> 00:12:33,283
And what he's saying is that we abstain from the obvious expressions of that, which is the destruction of life, the wanton destruction of life, from stealing, sexual misconduct, false speech, and from these wines and from intoxicants, anything that takes away our sense of

129
00:12:33,802 --> 00:13:01,144
moral responsibility and then of course there's the opposite to that which is complementary and that's generosity the last two you see accomplishments in generosity and the accomplishment of wisdom is seen as the arising and passing away phenomena in other words seeing that things are transient

130
00:13:02,136 --> 00:13:32,076
when we really see that things are transient then of course you don't you don't hold on to them your grip loosens and one of the measures of the spiritual life our own personal development is that you find much more joy in giving than in receiving that's one little test you can set yourself are you still are you still expecting people to give you things to make you happy

131
00:13:33,052 --> 00:14:02,399
but actually you get much more happiness by giving by giving away now when you give away you have to give something up and there's your relinquishment that's the undoing of that tightness that we have around things my this is mine and that's how wisdom grows you see through realizing through the deep realizing with the impermanence

132
00:14:02,701 --> 00:14:29,822
of things so if anything is if anything is impermanent it's obviously not reliable and therefore why should we be upset when things that we we love and hold on to and say are mine disappear or broken so if somebody gives you a very precious thing like a Ming vase you have to imagine it already broken so when it does break you're not upset

133
00:14:31,456 --> 00:14:33,818
That's the idea anyway.

134
00:14:35,981 --> 00:14:40,448
Remember that when it comes to things, actually you can only use them.

135
00:14:41,169 --> 00:14:48,519
The idea of possession is a legal fiction, isn't it?

136
00:14:48,539 --> 00:14:53,706
I mean, you might say, this is my car, see?

137
00:14:53,726 --> 00:14:54,727
And then a thief takes it.

138
00:14:54,948 --> 00:14:56,431
You still go around saying, this is my car.

139
00:14:57,852 --> 00:15:00,436
No, it's a thief's car.

140
00:15:00,456 --> 00:15:00,956
They've got it.

141
00:15:01,881 --> 00:15:03,604
But you still hold on to it as my car.

142
00:15:04,345 --> 00:15:06,687
I'm not suggesting that you shouldn't try and get it back, you understand.

143
00:15:06,989 --> 00:15:13,256
It's just the pain, the pain of somebody feeding your car, my car.

144
00:15:13,277 --> 00:15:21,267
So when you switch your thing from my car to a car I use, then the pain isn't so much, you see.

145
00:15:25,192 --> 00:15:31,500
So on this particular discourse, you see, he's sort of broadened it out a bit from the other stuff that we were

146
00:15:31,801 --> 00:15:33,003
that we were doing the other weeks.

147
00:15:36,086 --> 00:15:37,447
Very good.

148
00:15:37,467 --> 00:15:40,532
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

149
00:15:40,552 --> 00:15:44,937
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

150
00:15:51,085 --> 00:15:53,427
Well, that was very weak.

151
00:15:53,447 --> 00:15:55,530
It obviously wasn't a good talk.

152
00:15:55,551 --> 00:15:58,274
I mean, it just didn't get the response.

153
00:15:59,155 --> 00:16:00,356
Oh, that's terrible.

154
00:16:00,943 --> 00:16:03,225
laughter

